<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12013b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12013b">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12013b"> 13(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ~ Pres part app. to subject</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">J&apos;ai compris, mon cher ami. Vous faites le proc&egrave;s des phrases que jalonnent mollement les seuls adjectifs ou participes &eacute;pith&egrave;tes. On en pourrait donc tirer en fran&ccedil;ais deux r&egrave;gles de syntaxe et de style formelles. <i>Premi&egrave;re r&egrave;gle</i>: la proposition relative est, quoi qu&apos;en pense un vain peuple, plus l&eacute;g&egrave;re et mieux articul&eacute;e que la proposition dite participiale. <font color="green">[187]</font> <i>Deuxi&egrave;me r&egrave;gle</i>: tout participe pr&eacute;sent en apposition &agrave; un substantif qui ne joue point le r&ocirc;le de sujet, sera r&eacute;put&eacute; lourd et incorrect. <br>[I understand, dear friend. You argue against those phrases solely and weakly articulated by adjectives and descriptive participles used as adjectives. We could derive from this two rules of formal syntax and style in French. First rule: the relative clause is, contrary to shallow belief, lighter and clearer than the so-called participle clause. Second rule: each present participle affixed to a noun that does not have the function of subject, will be considered heavy and incorrect. <small> Jacques Boulenger &amp; Andr&eacute; Th&eacute;rive, <a name="SOIR" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#SOIR"><cite title="source">Les Soir&eacute;es du Grammaire-Club</cite></a> (1924) 187-8</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
